Schools are being encouraged to focus more on math, spelling and grammar
English literature courses will require students to study at least one play by Shakespeare, a 19th-century novel, romantic poetry and contemporary British novels from 1914 onwards.
&quot;Unseen texts&quot; are also included in the exam to encourage wider reading.
The combined course of English literature and language is abolished.
From 2015, students will be required to take a standalone GCSE for Language, although there are strong incentives to choose English Literature as a separate qualification.
The Department of Education will tomorrow publish the new syllabuses for English and Maths - the first subjects to be radically overhauled.
Other core courses will be changed next year.
In a separate initiative, Ofqual, the exams regulator, will announce a reorganization of GCSE structures, including a new grading system and less coursework.
In a speech over the summer, Education Secretary Michael Gove said there was &quot;a broad consensus that we need to reform our examination system to restore public confidence&quot;, stressing that GCSEs would become &quot;more challenging, more ambitious and more rigorous&quot;.
Studies show that English schools spend less time on maths – 116 hours a year, or three hours a week per school year – than most other countries.
In contrast, Australian schools teach an average of 143 hours per year and students in Singapore receive 138 hours.
While there will be no formal requirement to allocate more time to maths in the curriculum, coalition sources say the comprehensive maths test - combined with a greater weighting of the subject in rankings - is likely to encourage schools to allocate more hours.
More emphasis is placed on &quot;real life problems&quot; in the curriculum, including financial mathematics.
