Traveling through mud, rivers and jungles for free medical care
dr Georges Bwelle brings free medical aid to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend nearly every weekend treating hundreds of patients
There are not many doctors in the West African country, just one for every 5,000 people
Vote here or on your mobile device
dr Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 CNN Heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other heroes in the top 10 to vote for CNN Hero of the Year.
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue their extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his ailing father repeatedly pass out and travel to hospitals that did not have the resources to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first he just broke his arm, but then inflammation developed and spread to his brain, causing a hematoma that would affect him for the rest of his life.
&quot;There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,&quot; said Georges Bwelle.
We would have gotten him out of Cameroon if we had had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to crowded clinics and hospitals for the treatment they had to offer.
&quot;It&#39;s not easy,&quot; Bwelle comments.
You can leave home at five in the morning and run to the hospital to be first and not be first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has changed little since Bwelle&#39;s father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organization.
This compares to one doctor for every 413 people in the United States.
But even if there were a doctor for them, most Cameroonians could not afford the visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and nearly three-quarters of the country&#39;s health expenditure is private.
&quot;The only problem they have is poverty,&quot; says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
Seeing his father and so many of his countrymen suffer made Bwelle decide to do something about it.
dr Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers have performed 700 free surgeries in the last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people squeeze into minibuses and, with the medical equipment tied to the roof, drive across unpaved terrain to the villages that need help.
Things don&#39;t always go smoothly.
More than once they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are greeted like heroes: a feast, song and dance, and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is a real cause for celebration, and Bwelle - with his big smile and boundless energy - is happy to join in the happy celebration.
The next morning, the team then begins examining hundreds of patients.
&quot;We treat 500 people per trip,&quot; says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometers around the village - and on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a range of areas.
Many people are being treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates - a document required for school but many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evenings, the team performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
The surgeries usually take place in a school, town hall or apartment; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the recovery area to make room for the next one.
The lighting for the operating room and the disinfection equipment is powered by the group&#39;s generator, so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It&#39;s a busy schedule, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
&quot;They drum all night so we can stay up and get on with our work,&quot; says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team drives back to the city, tired but proud of the work they have done.
The group -- a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students -- have performed 700 free surgeries in the last year and know their work makes a huge difference to the people they help.
One man explained that the free hernia surgery he received now allows him to return to work.
&quot;It changes the future of my family,&quot; the man said.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job he finances 60% of his charitable work, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
&quot;I really don&#39;t know when he sleeps,&quot; says Katie O&#39;Malley, a sophomore in medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer in Bwelle&#39;s group.
He&#39;s always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization to go on these campaigns.
For US and European medical and nursing students like O&#39;Malley who support Bwelle, this is a chance to gain hands-on experience they would never get at home.
&quot;We can be present at surgeries where we help to swab blood or provide instruments for Dr. hold the Bwave,&quot; explains O&#39;Malley.
That would never be possible in America as a second-year medical student.
The students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and often bring donated medical supplies with them.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes care of accommodation, transport and guidance.
&quot;He&#39;s a hero without a doubt,&quot; says O&#39;Malley.
He dedicates his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no bounds.
The almost constant work is not a burden for Bwelle.
Helping others lead happier lives, fulfilling a promise he made to his father, brings him great joy.
&quot;I&#39;m so happy doing this work,&quot; says Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I&#39;m doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
