Pope Francis appoints first cardinals in February
Pope Francis will appoint new cardinals of the Catholic Church for the first time on February 22, the Vatican announced on Thursday.
Cardinals are the highest-ranking clergy in the Catholic Church after the pope, and they are the ones who elect a pope, so Francis will appoint the first group of men who will ultimately help choose his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, a cardinal who has reached the age of 80 can no longer vote in the papal election - that falls to a group of 120 &quot;eligible cardinals&quot;.
In a statement announcing the news, Father Federico Lombardi, a Vatican spokesman, said there would be a meeting of all cardinals before the ceremony to appoint the new cardinals, also known as the consistory.
&quot;Pope Francis has decided to announce in advance his decision to convene the Consistory in February so that other meetings requiring the participation of cardinals from around the world can be scheduled,&quot; Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said the number of cardinals eligible to vote will likely have fallen by February.
He explained that a pope normally appoints as many cardinals as necessary to bring the number of cardinals eligible to vote back to 120, and as many cardinals over 80 as he likes.
Next year&#39;s consistory is significant because it is the first since Francis was elected in March this year, Valero said.
At the moment there is a certain overhang on the part of Europe and especially Italy.
&quot;It will be interesting to see if the new pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore the balance,&quot; he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, yet they have only a tiny number of cardinals.
The cardinals will also be the first to be called since the formation of Francis&#39;s Council of Cardinals, a group of eight cardinals from around the world charged with finding ways to reform the Church.
In the past, the pope decided everything alone.
&quot;Now Francis has chosen these eight cardinals to help him,&quot; Valero said.
He said it was &quot;very possible&quot; that Francis would ask the cardinals for advice.
But we haven&#39;t been in this position before - it&#39;s all brand new.
Valero said that typically the bishops from big places would be appointed cardinals, but Francis is &quot;full of surprises - so we don&#39;t know who he is appointing&quot;.
