Is Europe&#39;s elite ready to do business with Britain?
Business for Britain was launched in April with the aim of bringing business around the table and defining what those who make Britain prosperous and jobs want to change in our relationship with the EU.
To do this, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey of UK business leaders, asking them what they think of the UK, the economy and the EU.
YouGov surveyed over 1,000 business executives, roughly representing UK business sizes, sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will surprise many.
We found that the vast majority of companies are now exporting outside of Europe, focusing on countries that are modernizing and growing while those in the EU are stagnating.
They want governments to favor new trade links with countries like China, India and Brazil, rather than dwell on the long and arduous process of reforming the EU&#39;s obscure institutions.
When asked for their views on specific regulatory issues - from antitrust to product legislation - the majority of business leaders believe control of these key competencies should be brought back to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction with the single market as businesses said the costs of Brussels regulations now outweigh the benefits of being part of Europe&#39;s trade zone - even 40 per cent of big companies agreed with those traditionally most pro-European.
Finally, and perhaps this says most, our survey of business leaders found that a clear majority would like the UK to steer a course towards deal change and a relationship with the EU based on trade, not politics.
This insight, shared by companies of all sizes and leading corporations, shows that the economy is pushing for a &quot;change that makes sense&quot; that will put the reins of business back in the UK.
A lot is at stake - changing the deal and giving Britain better terms would see 16 per cent change their minds in favor of staying in a referendum.
The Prime Minister should have no doubts: this poll shows that British business is behind his plan to renegotiate Britain&#39;s terms of EU membership.
It also shows that companies expect a significant shift in power back to the UK from a renegotiation.
A better deal for the UK economy is possible and increasingly necessary as the Eurozone moves towards closer economic and fiscal union.
The priority must be jobs and growth in the UK, the results of our survey show, which means an increased focus on trade for businesses and a fundamental shift in Brussels&#39; approach to regulation.
