Australian airlines are monitoring the decision, which is taking a lot of work for US airlines to implement, but have no immediate plans to change their rules.
Air traffic control authority CASA also said it would look into the announcement, but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic devices during critical flight phases in Australia still apply.
&quot;CASA currently has no specific regulations regarding the use of electronic devices on aircraft,&quot; it said.
The issue is subject to regulations that require airlines to maintain safety at all times and passengers to follow safety instructions given by cabin crew.
Virgin has already held talks with CASA about expanding the use of its in-flight Wi-Fi entertainment system, saying it is open to change but would need to be initiated by lawmakers.
&quot;We would welcome a review by CASA of electronic device approvals, which we believe would improve the customer experience now that we offer in-flight (wireless entertainment),&quot; a spokesman said.
Qantas said it would stick to the current rules for the time being.
&quot;Our current policy is that electronic devices cannot be used during takeoff and landing, and we have no plans at this time to change that,&quot; the company said.
FAA regulations apply to US airlines.
However, we are always interested in regulatory developments that can benefit passengers and will certainly look closely at the FAA&#39;s decision and the reasons behind it.
The decision affects US companies differently depending on the age of the fleet.
They must demonstrate that their aircraft can tolerate mobile device interference and amend manuals, training materials, carry-on programs and customer briefings.
&quot;After an airline confirms its fleet&#39;s tolerance, it can allow passengers to use portable, lightweight electronic devices such as tablets, e-book readers and smartphones at any altitude,&quot; the FAA said.
In rare instances of poor visibility, the crew will instruct passengers to turn off their devices during landing.
The group also recommended stowing heavier equipment securely under the seat or in the overhead compartments during takeoff and landing.
