Scientists have been able to shed more light on how a dog&#39;s tail wag is related to its mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs wagged their tails more to the right (from the dog&#39;s perspective), while nervous dogs wagged their tails to the left.
But now scientists say other dogs can sense and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: &quot;In humans, it is well known that the left and right hemispheres of the brain respond differently to stimuli that evoke positive or negative emotions.&quot;
Here we tried to look at this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, like in humans, the right side of the brain is responsible for left side movement and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to their fellow dogs wagging their tails sideways, the researchers monitored the animals while they watched videos of other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged friends and analyzed their behavior.
We&#39;ll probably soon understand why the tail sometimes moves one way and sometimes the other
Professor Vallortigara said: &quot;We showed the dogs films with dogs - either a lifelike version or a silhouette to eliminate other distracting aspects and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or to the right.&quot;
When the animals saw an otherwise expressionless dog wag its tail to the right (from the wagging dog&#39;s perspective), they remained completely relaxed.
However, when the tail tilt was predominantly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog wagging), their heart rate increased and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs don&#39;t intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he believes that the dogs learned from experience which movements to worry about and when not to.
He said, &quot;When you have multiple encounters with other dogs and wagging your tail in one direction is more likely to be associated with friendly behavior and the right side is more likely to produce less friendly behavior, then you react based on those experiences.&quot;
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers better understand their pet&#39;s emotions.
John Bradshaw, a canine behavior expert and visiting fellow at the University of Bristol&#39;s Veterinary School, said this was not the first study to look at whether left and right are important for dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they&#39;re looking at an aggressive dog and to the right when they&#39;re looking at a contented dog.
Another research paper at the University of Victoria in Canada stated: &quot;Dogs are more likely to approach a robotic dog when its &#39;tail&#39; wags to the left rather than to the right, rather than fidgeting -- exactly the opposite of what it was in the Italian study.&quot;
He said the differences could be because the dogs in the different studies didn&#39;t interpret the animals in the movies or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs respond to real dogs could help, he explained.
&quot;While there is considerable evidence in many different mammals that the two hemispheres are used for different purposes, many of the details have yet to be determined - and dogs are no exception,&quot; Bradshaw said.
But since their behavior is easy to record, it probably won&#39;t be long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves one way and sometimes the other.
