Pawn shops boom in Singapore as crisis hits middle class
At a pawn shop in Singapore&#39;s Bendemeer shopping mall, Janani Amirthalinga trades a gold bracelet, ring and pair of earrings to pay for her daughters&#39; school fees.
&quot;My husband and I just bought a house, all my money is in it,&quot; says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns 3,000 Singapore dollars (approx. 1,730 euros) every month as an administrative employee and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not enough, she explains.
In fact, demand is so great in parts of Southeast Asia -- where household debt is mounting -- that ValueMax, where it made its swap, became the third pawn shop to list on the Singapore stock exchange this week.
Pawning jewelry is not only a quick way to get money — S$1,300 in Janani Amirthalinga&#39;s case — it&#39;s almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, pawnshops in Singapore charge an APR of 17 percent, just above the 15.4 percent charged by United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawnshops offer the advantage that no credit checks or proof of income are required, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
That&#39;s why millions of people across the region are turning to pawnshops as families feel the pressure of rising living costs and mounting household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and easy credit thanks to loose fiscal policies in developed economies, lower- and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to make up the difference in a faltering economy.
This week, rating agency Standard &amp; Poor&#39;s identified growing household debt, mainly from rising mortgages, as a risk factor for Asian banks&#39; creditworthiness.
According to the agency, Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in relation to gross domestic product in Asia.
Malaysia tops the list with 80 percent of GDP, up from 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also worried about high levels of consumer debt in Thailand, which narrowly emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, data showed ongoing weakness in exports and a slacking in consumer demand.
&quot;The bottom line is that as costs rise, people in the middle to lower bracket (of the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible,&quot; says Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historic highs in gold prices over the past two years have fueled the trend toward pledging personal items as people take the opportunity to turn family jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of pawned items at the city-state&#39;s 200 pawnshops are gold.
People say to themselves, &quot;Gold prices are looking good, let&#39;s pawn grandmother&#39;s gold chain and get it back next month.&quot;
Thailand&#39;s largest pawn shop operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 percent increase in customers at its branches in recent months.
The growth in the deposit business is so strong that ValueMax, which operates the branch in Bendemeer and 15 others in Singapore, is looking to expand not only into neighboring Malaysia - where the company has four stores - but also outside of Asia, according to Yeah Lee Ching, managing director by ValueMax.
The company is funding it with 60 percent of the $66 million it raised in the Singapore IPO this week.
While some lenders have been caught in the crossfire for high interest rates, Yeah explains that not only do pawnshops offer cheaper rates than other lenders, but they don&#39;t directly add to the debt.
&quot;Customers are lending on items they already own, and liquefying personal valuables doesn&#39;t increase household debt,&quot; she explains.
The pawnbroking business is increasingly being socially accepted as short-term, secured financing.
Also, not all people who use pawn shops are in financial difficulties.
Rich Singaporeans also come to ValueMax stores to pawn gold bars and Rolex watches, receiving up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Customers come to us from every social class.
&quot;These include wealthy people borrowing short-term for a business or investment, or small businesses that need to bridge cash flow bottlenecks,&quot; says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
