Syria has destroyed its ability to produce chemical weapons, according to a monitoring group
Syria has destroyed key facilities producing chemical weapons and poison gas munitions, the Global Chemical Weapons Monitoring Group said Thursday, while heavy clashes erupted in the north of the country near one of the sites suspected of storing toxic substances.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group announced that more than 120,000 people had been killed since the civil war began almost three years ago.
The announcement by the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) came a day before the deadline on
November 1 set by The Hague-based organization Damascus to destroy or render &quot;inoperable&quot; all chemical weapons manufacturing facilities, including all machines for mixing chemicals into poison gas and loading ammunition.
The completion of this process, which is essentially the first stage of destruction, is a major milestone in an ambitious timeline aimed at eliminating all of Syria&#39;s chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of the facilities means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
However, Damascus has yet to begin destroying existing weapons and supplies.
There are believed to be around 1,000 tons of chemicals and weapons in the country, including mustard gas and the nerve agent sarin.
The announcement came at a time when fighting was raging Thursday in the town of Safira, which experts say has a chemical weapons production facility and storage facilities, according to the UK-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights.
The activist group, which tracks the death toll through a network of activists in Syria, said Thursday 120,296 people had died.
Of these, 61,067 are civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the government side, 29,954 of them belonged to President Bashar Assad&#39;s army, 18,678 were pro-government fighters and 187 were Lebanese Hezbollah militias.
Also among the dead were 2,202 deserted army soldiers and 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
On July 25, the UN estimated the number of dead in this conflict since March 2011 at 100,000.
This number has not yet been updated.
The conflict has forced around two million people to flee the country.
Assad&#39;s troops have been fighting the rebels in Safira for weeks, many of whom have ties to al-Qaeda groups.
The observatory said there were casualties on both sides on Thursday but gave no details.
The fighting underscores the danger chemical weapons inspectors face as their mission to rid Syria of its toxic weapons arsenal is a race against time amid a raging civil war.
According to the OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, the team &quot;is now confident that they have seen and witnessed the destruction of all key manufacturing and blending/filling facilities identified by Syria.&quot;
Therefore, &quot;no further inspection activities are currently planned.&quot;
Earlier in the week, inspectors said they had completed the first round of inspections, visiting 21 out of 23 sites specified by Damascus.
Visits to two facilities were not possible due to safety concerns, inspectors said.
On Thursday, the OPWC said the two sites had been &quot;abandoned... and the chemical weapons program assets there had been moved to other named facilities, which were inspected,&quot; according to the Syrian statement.
It was not immediately clear if the Safira site was one of the two facilities that the OPCW inspectors were not able to visit.
Syria has presented a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons, which must be approved by the OPWC Executive Committee next month.
&quot;I salute the bravery and courage you all have shown in accomplishing the most challenging mission ever undertaken by this organization,&quot; said Ahmed Uzumcu, director-general of the monitoring organization in a commentary released by the OPCW.
For three years now, the mainly Sunni Muslim rebels have been fighting in this civil war against Assad&#39;s government and its security forces, which include many members of the Alawites, a splinter group of Shiite Islam.
Regarding further developments, monitoring group head Rami Abdurrahman said there was a powerful explosion at an air defense facility in Syria&#39;s coastal Latakia province on Wednesday.
