Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in children&#39;s health and family issues.
Should a mother be concerned if her daughter is growing breasts and pubic hair by the age of seven or eight?
At the annual American Academy of Pediatrics conference this week in Orlando, Fla., pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz that these early physical changes are relatively normal among American girls and represent a new norm.
&quot;I spend a lot of time reassuring parents -- it&#39;s not usually a sign that puberty is about to hit,&quot; Kaplowitz explained.
Obvious indicators of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair, and body odor, show up earlier in girls.
However, there has been only a slight shift in the age of menarche (onset of the first menstrual period) over the past 40 years.
