&quot;Once breast development begins, it&#39;s at least another two to three years before menarche occurs,&quot; said Kaplowitz, also author of Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Dealing with This Common Problem.
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
There is some debate as to what actually marks the onset of puberty, but it is considered &quot;precocious&quot; when breast augmentation is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows or stagnates—something a pediatrician can closely monitor.
If it is progressing more quickly, testing by an endocrinologist may be indicated to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay early menstruation and ward off another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to stunted growth and short stature in adults.
The recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the child&#39;s age, speed of development, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious about drugs, but he concedes, &quot;Suppressing puberty can mitigate behavior problems and girls&#39; feelings of being different from their peers.&quot;
The other big problem is understandable: parents just don&#39;t want their very young daughters to have their periods.
&quot;They worry about the risk of pregnancy or how they&#39;re managing the hygiene side,&quot; Kaplowitz said.
&quot;It was a shock,&quot; recalls a woman whose daughter started her period when she was 10.
Even though there were early signs and we&#39;d talked about menstruation, she wasn&#39;t emotionally prepared.
She came home from school scared and excited because she was the first in her group of friends.
There are many well-publicized theories about the causes of precocious puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are causal.
Boys reach puberty earlier than girls.
Kaplowitz believes the most compelling premise is the obesity epidemic.
He helped conduct a study in 2001 on girls aged six to nine linking body fat to puberty.
Other research supports this conclusion, but there are many other factors at play.
In this country, African American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another conundrum: Although boys grow facial and pubic hair earlier, the trend towards full early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other physicians at the AAP conference underscored the complexity of the issue.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in babies and toddlers.
&quot;We have to be careful how we identify the true onset of puberty,&quot; said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children&#39;s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to seek advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
&quot;That can mean having to have a conversation sooner than expected,&quot; Kaplowitz advised.
If you remain calm, the child usually responds well.
Girls who bloom early need reassurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it comes sooner than expected.
