George Kerevan: European unbundling gives the Scots a choice
Another day, another independence horror story.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland is required to join the Schengen area as a condition of EU membership.
This provides the cue for tales of passport control at Berwick and a barbed wire border along Hadrian&#39;s Wall.
Indeed, the Strathclyde bill did point to the potential economic benefits of being able to travel more freely across the rest of Europe, but – as expected – this didn&#39;t make the headlines.
Nor has anyone mentioned that EU member states often bend their strict rules when it is more convenient for them.
As Scotland is currently not part of the Schengen area, continued non-compliance would be just a small concession for Brussels in exchange for what it really wants from the Scots.
So actually no story.
And one that&#39;s so aged it&#39;s already a fossil: I first heard the &quot;independence means passport controls&quot; duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this age-old story.
Why should an independent Scotland be expected to dance to European tunes?
Why trade the yoke of London for that of Brussels, especially now?
This is the real European news: the grand post-war plan to unify Europe has stalled.
With the euro crisis, the European project officially died.
All over the EU, parties that are hostile to the EU or want to jettison the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party – founded just this year – garnered almost five million votes in September&#39;s general election, effectively driving the Free Democrats (the equivalent of Britain&#39;s Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis is proving to be a turning point.
Because of the tough austerity policies imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, combined with the straitjacket that sticking to the common currency is forcing national economies into, many people believe the European project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running excessive budget deficits – this was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has locked its members on exchange rates that are favorable to German exporters – and German politicians would like to leave it that way.
Without the possibility of a local currency devaluation, Southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage compared to Germany.
The only option is to cut wages and public spending - spurred on by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and currency problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of Brussels-enacted &quot;green&quot; energy policies - a code for subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers - European industry is paying twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as the United States.
That&#39;s a crippling cost disadvantage, as we saw at Grangemouth.
All the wage locks in the world do nothing to protect the European petrochemical industry from being cornered by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is brewing, particularly in France, once the EU&#39;s cheerleader.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany in check and put Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policies on Europe, with the ailing French economy struggling.
The result: Marine Le Pen&#39;s right-wing, anti-EU Front National has just won a crucial by-election, relegating the ruling Socialists to third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 per cent of the vote - a timely warning to Britain&#39;s Labor Party that it cannot assume a split on the right would automatically benefit the left.
What is Le Pen doing with her newfound popularity among working-class white French?
She wants to use next year&#39;s EU elections to forge an anti-EU, anti-common currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections – which is very possible – then such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament for the first time.
This is my point: in the not too distant future, growing resentment against the EU and the single currency will converge towards the abolition of the euro.
The EU will not go away, but it will become more like the &quot;Europe of (sovereign) nations&quot; favored by General de Gaulle.
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may stick with the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in hopes of ingratiating itself with the US.
However, Washington&#39;s growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all this?
We can choose to be a region of (ultimately) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – which includes telling Berlin and Brussels what to put where.
I suspect Scotland could fare quite well in a looser Europe as long as we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other, similarly thinking countries is easier in a non-federated Europe of Nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same as Norway and keeping our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is - remarkably - the most successful anti-austerity political movement in Europe, winning a spectacular majority in 2011 by rejecting proposed (and implemented) cuts by Labor Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory Lib Dem coalition were responsible for.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to have austerity policies imposed by Berlin and Brussels.
FAA: Airline Passengers Can Now Use Electronic Devices On Planes (But Can&#39;t Make Cell Phone Calls)
From departure to landing, air travelers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play games, listen to music and watch movies, but not use their cell phones, according to new guidelines released Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA). were published in the United States.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented depends on the airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta explained at a press conference.
Airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated flight crew training manuals and equipment stowage policies to reflect the new regulations.
The FAA said it has already received plans from some airlines to increase the use of portable electronic devices on airplanes.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
&quot;Depending on the status of the plan, we may authorize expanded use of electronic devices very soon,&quot; the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers are required to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when aircraft doors are closed.
You can only start them again when the plane has reached an altitude of three kilometers and the captain gives the green light.
Upon entering the landing approach, passengers must turn them off and not restart them until the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose planes are secured against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices during take-off, landing and on the tarmac, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aviators that have been converted to use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, President of the Association of Professional Flight Attendants, welcomed the changes.
&quot;If the new rule is implemented safely - and we are working closely with the airline on this - both sides will benefit,&quot; commented Glading.
