Last month, National Transportation Safety Board safety expert Mark Rosenker, national transportation safety expert, told CBS News cellphones are still considered a risk.
&quot;Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially interfere with navigation devices, but because we at the FCC know that airborne transmissions can also interfere with cell towers,&quot; Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee created by the FAA to study the issue recommended last month that the government allow more widespread use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure has increased on the FAA to relax restrictions on its use.
Critics, such as Democratic Missouri Sen. Claire McCaskill, argue that there are no valid safety reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce as device usage has become ubiquitous.
Some studies report that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore switching off the device.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air travelers in 1966 after reports of FM radios being carried by passengers, which was the latest technology at the time, interfering with navigational and communications equipment.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA to be immune to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering Wi-Fi to passengers when flying at altitude for a number of years.
The fliers adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also less sensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger planes should be eligible for increased use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today&#39;s electronic devices generally emit far less radio frequency emissions than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, only emit minimal radiation when you turn the page.
But when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
Amazon.com is among the proponents of easing restrictions on passenger device use.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and did a test flight to identify problems, but couldn&#39;t find any.
FAA Advisory Committee members expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using devices.
Douglas Kidd, of the National Association of Airline Passengers, said he believed the interference from the devices was real, although the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said there were only anecdotal reports from pilots suggesting the devices were interfering with aircraft systems, and most of them were very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to instruct passengers to turn off instruments during instrument landings in poor visibility.
A travel industry group welcomed the changes, calling them a sensible adjustment for today&#39;s highly tech-savvy travelers.
