New anti-nicotine vaccine could put an end to the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could spoil the fun of smoking.
A single dose of the vaccine could protect mice from nicotine addiction for life.
More trials are needed before testing in humans, which may take years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said early results are good.
&quot;We are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy will one day help millions of smokers who have tried to quit using all the methods available on the market, but have found their nicotine addiction to be stronger than these approaches,&quot; said Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain the genetic information needed to produce nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a steady stream of antibodies.
The antibodies hunt the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, preventing a smoker from experiencing a nicotine high.
In experiments, vaccinated mice given nicotine maintained their normal level of activity.
Unvaccinated mice, on the other hand, took a &quot;time-out,&quot; the researchers explained, a sign the nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
Vaccinations had to be given so frequently to maintain antibody levels that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be significantly lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal has said, if a future human vaccine is completely safe, it could be given to children before they are tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
More likely, though, smokers would use it to quit.
&quot;They know that if they start smoking again, because of the nicotine vaccine, they won&#39;t enjoy it anymore, and that will help them break the habit,&quot; he says.
British scientists said the results were interesting but warned more research was needed.
