Frontier Airlines charges carry-on baggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 from passengers who wish to stow carry-on luggage on their flight.
Frontier Airlines intends to charge up to $100 for a carry-on bag and $2 for coffee or soda, though Wednesday&#39;s announcement said passengers could keep the whole can.
The new fee applies to carry-on baggage in the overhead bin, small bags under the seat are still free.
Frontier said it charges $25 if the fee is prepaid and $100 for travelers who pay at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O&#39;Malley said the $100 fee is aimed at encouraging travelers to arrange payment up front.
&quot;We don&#39;t want to calculate that amount,&quot; she explained.
Airlines began charging first and second checked bags in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these have therefore stuffed as much as they can into carry-on luggage, with the result that the overhead bins are often overcrowded.
Fees are a way of encouraging passengers to take less on board.
O&#39;Malley said the new fee isn&#39;t really about making money.
It is about Frontier&#39;s most loyal customers, who have made it clear that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find space in the compartment above the seat.
Passengers who buy their tickets on the airline&#39;s website do not have to pay.
This means that a passenger at the Frontier gate may be allowed one bag for free, but the next person may have to pay $100 for a comparable bag.
O&#39;Malley said Frontier&#39;s website and check-in procedures are changing so that passengers are aware of the fee before they get to the gate.
Frontier&#39;s new carry-on fee will not come into effect until the summer, and there is no exact date yet.
Passengers often complain about baggage surcharges and other fees, but airlines are happy to resort to them.
They argue that luggage transport costs money and passengers should pay for this service if they want it.
Many on Wall Street are taking the new bag fees as a sign that airlines are making enough money to pay for air travel after years of losses.
So far, however, most have avoided hand luggage fees.
Spirit Airlines Inc. was the first to charge carry-on bags three years ago, followed later by Allegiant Air, another low-cost carrier.
The only other airline with such a fee is Hungary&#39;s Wizz Air, said airline consultant Jay Sorensen, who is closely following the surcharge.
He estimated in a December 2011 report that the carry-on fee brings in $50 million annually for Spirit.
Sorensen, who previously held an executive position at Midwest Airlines, recently flew Spirit and was curious what to expect at the gate when passengers were confronted with the company&#39;s unusual carry-on fee.
&quot;The boarding process was among the smoothest I&#39;ve experienced in my aviation career,&quot; he said.
I expected to see gnashing of teeth and physical arguments at the gate.
&quot;The plane was full,&quot; he explained, &quot;and boarding went like clockwork.&quot;
Frontier also follows Spirit on the $2 they charge for coffee, tea, soda, or juice.
