US road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the deteriorating highway system and believe they have found the solution in a small black box that fits on the dashboard of every car.
The devices, which record every mile driven and report the information to authorities, are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and state planning bureaus to overhaul the outdated system of funding US roads.
The normally rather boring field of road planning has suddenly sparked an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups and are arguing that the government should be able to use the small boxes to record miles driven - and possibly where driven - and then use the information to calculate tax returns.
The Tea Party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and has raised a number of privacy concerns.
But while Congress can&#39;t agree on a course of action, several states aren&#39;t waiting any longer.
They are currently studying how they can move to a system where drivers pay per mile driven over the next ten years.
