When fuel prices are high, politicians don&#39;t dare raise the tax by even one cent.
&quot;The gas tax just isn&#39;t sustainable,&quot; said Lee Munnich, a transportation law expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently fitted 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
&quot;It represents the most sensible long-term alternative,&quot; he said.
Bureaucrats refer to it as a mile-based user fee.
Unsurprisingly, the idea has found favor with urban liberals, as the tax could be used to influence driving behavior to reduce congestion and climate-damaging emissions, for example.
California planners rely on the system to develop strategies to meet the state&#39;s ambitious statutory climate change goals.
But Pennsylvania Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also said he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The independent marketers at the Reason Foundation are also impressed by the idea of having drivers pay based on the distance they have traveled.
&quot;This isn&#39;t a black hole tax,&quot; explains Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also backed by two former US Secretary of Transportation, who in a 2011 report urged Congress to move toward mileage-based billing.
The US Senate last year approved a $90 million pilot project that would have included 10,000 cars.
But a majority in the House of Representatives blocked the move, responding to concerns from rural lawmakers who represent people who often have to travel long distances to get to work or into town on a daily basis.
Several states and major cities are nonetheless moving in this direction on their own.
The most dedicated is Oregon, which is currently recruiting 5,000 drivers for the country&#39;s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon be paying the mileage fee to the state instead of the fuel tax.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering one.
Illinois is testing it with trucks on a limited basis.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transportation departments of 17 East Coast states (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is studying how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently fitted with the devices, drivers were wary of the government tracking their every move.
&quot;Big Brother concerns and things like that were a big issue,&quot; said Alauddin Khan, director of strategy and results management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn&#39;t want it.
As the test began, the Nevada ACLU warned on its website, &quot;It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into full-fledged surveillance devices.&quot;
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on individuals&#39; daily movements.
Nevada is among a number of states that are now looking to affordable technology that would allow the state to track mileage, but not exactly when and where.
With that, according to Khan, the public would also be more reassured.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup in California called True Mileage.
The company didn&#39;t originally start out to help states tax drivers.
Rather, their goal was to gain a foothold in an emerging market for auto insurance that requires drivers to pay based on miles driven.
However, the devices she tested are also of interest to road planners because they do not work with GPS and only provide limited information that is regularly uploaded via modem.
&quot;People are more willing to participate if their speeds and locations aren&#39;t recorded,&quot; said Ryan Morrison, managing director of True Mileage.
Big mistakes were made in some of these public pilot programs.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving motorists a variety of choices.
You can opt for a device with or without GPS.
Or they choose not to use any device at all and instead pay a flat fee based on the average miles driven by all residents in the state.
Other agencies hope to sell the concept to a suspicious public by adding more features to the devices rather than fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a taxation device that will also pay for parking, pay for mileage-only insurance, and collect real-time speed data from other vehicles to help drivers avoid traffic jams.
&quot;Drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits offered by the system,&quot; according to a city planning document.
Some transportation planners, however, are wondering if all the talk about paying per mile is just a huge red herring.
Officials at the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area said Congress could solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund simply by raising fuel taxes.
An additional one-time fee or annual levy could be imposed on drivers with hybrid or other fuel-efficient vehicles so that they too pay their fair share.
&quot;There&#39;s no need for surgery when an aspirin will do,&quot; said Randy Rentschler, the commission&#39;s head of legislation and public affairs.
