The blockade policy doesn&#39;t excuse Obamacare&#39;s website problems, the drone strikes
Obama&#39;s 2008 campaign memoir is a sad reminder of what could have been
Nathaniel P. Morris is a sophomore at Harvard Medical School.
I am currently reading a terribly sad book.
It&#39;s a book that I thought would cheer me up and give me hope during my dreary sophomore year in med school.
It&#39;s called &quot;The Audacity to Win&quot; and chronicles Barack Obama&#39;s 2008 presidential election memoir.
When I finish my patient notes at night and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and speeches could take your breath away.
The election was a landslide victory and news anchors paused to reflect on the historic significance of the hour.
My classmates cried for joy and my parents collected all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on its way to the White House and the nation was poised for change.
When Obama took office back in 2008, he had approval ratings of 82%.
And then I close the book.
Switching back to the present is a rude awakening, like being jerked out of a dream.
Those optimistic times are hard to remember - they seem like a vague memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first voted, something has indeed changed.
But it&#39;s just not something I could have imagined.
I recognize the great and multifaceted things Obama has accomplished, from passing the Affordable Care Act on health insurance to the military pullout from Iraq, ending the army&#39;s forced silence on homosexuality, and killing Osama bin Laden.
I agree that partisan deadlock tactics have overturned too many aspirations designed to move our nation forward: immigration reform, a public health insurance option, and the closing of Guantanamo Bay, to name a few.
But after defending the Obama administration countless times to colleagues and acquaintances, I have come to the end of my attempts at explanations.
I&#39;ve reached a point of political despair.
The Republican blockade policy cannot explain why they allow foreign heads of state to be wiretapped or drones to kill innocent children overseas.
It fails to explain why the National Security Agency collects data on Americans&#39; private lives and why whistleblowers who expose government misconduct are punished.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, a US citizen, was assassinated without trial, nor why public funding and spending limits are being circumvented during the presidential election.
It does not justify the findings of a report that said the White House&#39;s efforts to silence the media were &quot;the most aggressive...since the Nixon administration.&quot;
And most recently, it cannot excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the Affordable Care Act was passed.
I don&#39;t know if that&#39;s what I should have expected.
Should I have understood when I was 18 that government work could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it?
Obviously, MP is not a predictable course, with an opposition party and fortuitous events like the Newtown massacre dominating the public debate.
But when I look at the examples above, they seem to be largely self-elected.
And that bothers me the most.
I re-elected Obama in 2012 not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confusing and half-baked alternative, seemingly unable to determine his direction and positions.
I felt that a second term for Obama, free from the pressures of future elections, would fulfill the hope we had been hearing about for so long.
But with Obama&#39;s approval ratings falling below 45% this week, this book has made the return to 2008 all the harder.
It awakens in me the longing for the many promises that have vanished into thin air.
This week I read a section in the book that describes how Obama suffered a heavy loss to Clinton in the Pennsylvania primary.
In a meeting with campaign officials after the decision, he told his staff they needed to get back on track and follow the purpose of their cause.
&quot;I want us to find our magic again,&quot; he said.
We must remember who we are.
It&#39;s five years later, Mr. President, and I couldn&#39;t agree with you more.
The views expressed in this commentary are those of Nathaniel Morris only.
